<HEADLINE>
VIOLINIST TO GIVE RECITALS IN FOUR-LEG TOUR ACROSS TAIWAN
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, March 13 (CNA) 03/13/07  18:19:01 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
The principal violinist of Taiwan's string orchestra, Taiwan
Connection, will begin a four-leg tour across Taiwan beginning
March 22 to give a series of solo performances.
</P>
<P>
Wu Meng-ping, who has visited the Koo Foundation Sun Yat-sen
Cancer Center frequently to entertain patients with his
performances, will give a series of violin recitals in Kaohsiung,
Chiayi, Yuanlin township in Changhua County, and Taipei.
</P>
<P>
The works he will play will include Johannes Brahms' "Violin
Sonata No. 1 in G major, Rain," Robert Schumann's "Fantasy in C
major, Op. 17," works by Romanian composers and violinists,
including George Enesco, and Maurice Ravel's "Gypsy."
</P>
<P>
The four recitals are scheduled for March 22 at the Kaohsiung
Cultural Center, March 26 at Chiayi University's Wenhui Hall,
March 28 at the Yuanlin Performance Hall, and March 20 at the
National Recital Hall in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Wu, a native of Taipei, graduated from Taiwan National Arts
Academy as a violin major and went to Germany in 1992 to pursue
further study at the Detmold Music Academy.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 he received the Kloster Frenswegen Scholarship to attend
the Niedersachen Chamber Music Camp.  A year later he won a
scholarship to begin studies at the Hans Eisler Academy in
Berlin. While at the academy he performed the Shostakovich Second
Violin Concerto with the Hans Eisler Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
He graduated from the academy in 1999 and received the highest
musical diploma attainable in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Wu has performed widely throughout Taiwan. In March 1998 he
received the honor of performing a solo recital in the National
Recital Hall in Taipei. An enthusiast of orchestral chamber
music, he has been a member of the Munich, Detmold and Taipei
Philharmonic Chamber Orchestras.
</P>
<P>
In 2000 Wu was selected to serve as Concertmaster of Academy of
Taiwan Strings.
</P>
